You can create a Button by passing texture file paths to the constructor:

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn_normal.png', 'btn_pressed.png', 'btn_disabled.png');
btn.setPosition(200, 300);
this.addChild(btn);
```

The third argument is the disabled-state texture (optional). You can also use `ccui.Widget.PLIST_TEXTURE` as a fourth argument if your textures come from a sprite sheet:

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn_normal.png', 'btn_pressed.png', '', ccui.Widget.PLIST_TEXTURE);
```

Use the `ccui.Text` constructor with three arguments:

```typescript
const label = new ccui.Text('Hello World', 'Arial', 24);
label.setPosition(cc.director.getWinSize().width / 2, 300);
this.addChild(label);
```

You can also use the static factory:
```typescript
const label = ccui.Text.create('Hello World', 'Arial', 24);
```

After creation, update the text with `label.setString('New text')` and change color with `label.setTextColor(cc.color(255, 0, 0))`.

Create a Layout, set the background color type to solid, then set the color:

```typescript
const panel = new ccui.Layout();
panel.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
panel.setBackGroundColorType(ccui.Layout.BG_COLOR_SOLID);
panel.setBackGroundColor(cc.color(0, 0, 0));
panel.setBackGroundColorOpacity(180);
panel.setPosition(100, 100);
this.addChild(panel);
```

Available background types: `ccui.Layout.BG_COLOR_NONE`, `ccui.Layout.BG_COLOR_SOLID`, `ccui.Layout.BG_COLOR_GRADIENT`.

Pass the frame name and the PLIST_TEXTURE constant:

```typescript
const img = new ccui.ImageView('icon_star.png', ccui.Widget.PLIST_TEXTURE);
img.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(img);
```

To load from a regular file instead:
```typescript
const img = new ccui.ImageView('res/images/icon_star.png');
// or
const img2 = new ccui.ImageView('res/images/icon_star.png', ccui.Widget.LOCAL_TEXTURE);
```

You can change the texture later with `img.loadTexture('other.png', ccui.Widget.LOCAL_TEXTURE)`.

Create the TextField with placeholder text, then enable and set the max length:

```typescript
const tf = new ccui.TextField('Enter your name...', 'Arial', 20);
tf.setMaxLengthEnabled(true);
tf.setMaxLength(16);
tf.setPosition(200, 300);
this.addChild(tf);
```

You can also enable password mode:
```typescript
tf.setPasswordEnabled(true);
```

Read the current value with `tf.getString()` and set it programmatically with `tf.setString('text')`.

