instruction:
Fix the bug in this code. The button click handler never fires:

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png', 'btn_pressed.png');
btn.setPosition(200, 200);
btn.setEnabled(false);
btn.addClickEventListener(() => {
    cc.log('clicked');
});
this.addChild(btn);
```

output:
The bug is that `setEnabled(false)` disables all interaction, including click events. The button cannot receive touches when disabled.

**Fix:** Set enabled to true (or remove the setEnabled call):

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png', 'btn_pressed.png');
btn.setPosition(200, 200);
btn.setEnabled(true); // must be true for clicks to work
btn.addClickEventListener(() => {
    cc.log('clicked');
});
this.addChild(btn);
```

instruction:
Fix the bug. The ScrollView does not scroll even though content is added:

```typescript
const sv = new ccui.ScrollView();
sv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
sv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);
sv.setPosition(50, 50);
for (let i = 0; i < 20; i++) {
    const item = new ccui.Text('Item ' + i, 'Arial', 18);
    item.setPosition(150, 380 - i * 40);
    sv.addChild(item);
}
this.addChild(sv);
```

output:
The bug is that `setInnerContainerSize` was never called. The inner container defaults to the same size as the ScrollView, so there's nothing to scroll.

**Fix:** Set the inner container size to be taller than the ScrollView and add items to the inner container:

```typescript
const sv = new ccui.ScrollView();
sv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
sv.setInnerContainerSize(cc.size(300, 800)); // must be > 400
sv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);
sv.setPosition(50, 50);
for (let i = 0; i < 20; i++) {
    const item = new ccui.Text('Item ' + i, 'Arial', 18);
    item.setPosition(150, 780 - i * 40);
    sv.getInnerContainer().addChild(item); // add to inner container
}
this.addChild(sv);
```

instruction:
Fix the bug. The layout children overlap instead of stacking vertically:

```typescript
const layout = new ccui.Layout();
layout.setSize(cc.size(300, 500));
layout.setLayoutType(ccui.Layout.ABSOLUTE);
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
    layout.addChild(btn);
}
this.addChild(layout);
```

output:
The bug is that the layout type is `ABSOLUTE`, which means children are freely positioned and don't auto-stack. Change it to `LINEAR_VERTICAL`:

```typescript
const layout = new ccui.Layout();
layout.setSize(cc.size(300, 500));
layout.setLayoutType(ccui.Layout.LINEAR_VERTICAL);
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
    const param = new ccui.LinearLayoutParameter();
    param.setGravity(ccui.LinearLayoutParameter.CENTER_HORIZONTAL);
    param.setMargin(new ccui.Margin(0, 5, 0, 0));
    btn.setLayoutParameter(param);
    layout.addChild(btn);
}
layout.forceDoLayout();
this.addChild(layout);
```

instruction:
Fix the bug. The widget's touch listener callback receives wrong `this` context:

```typescript
class MyLayer extends cc.Layer {
    score: number = 0;
    init() {
        const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
        btn.addTouchEventListener(function(sender, type) {
            if (type === ccui.Widget.TOUCH_ENDED) {
                this.score += 10;
            }
        });
        this.addChild(btn);
    }
}
```

output:
The bug is using a `function` keyword callback without passing `this` as the target. Inside a regular function, `this` does not refer to the MyLayer instance.

**Fix:** Either pass `this` as the second argument or use an arrow function:

```typescript
class MyLayer extends cc.Layer {
    score: number = 0;
    init() {
        const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
        // Option 1: pass target
        btn.addTouchEventListener((sender, type) => {
            if (type === ccui.Widget.TOUCH_ENDED) {
                this.score += 10;
            }
        }, this);
        this.addChild(btn);
    }
}
```

instruction:
Fix the bug. The LoadingBar fills from right to left instead of left to right:

```typescript
const bar = new ccui.LoadingBar('bar.png', 50);
bar.setDirection(ccui.LoadingBar.TYPE_RIGHT);
bar.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(bar);
```

output:
The bug is using `TYPE_RIGHT` which fills from right to left. For left-to-right filling, use `TYPE_LEFT`:

```typescript
const bar = new ccui.LoadingBar('bar.png', 50);
bar.setDirection(ccui.LoadingBar.TYPE_LEFT);
bar.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(bar);
```

`TYPE_LEFT` means the bar starts from the left and grows rightward. `TYPE_RIGHT` starts from the right and grows leftward.

instruction:
Fix the bug. The CheckBox event fires but isSelected always returns true:

```typescript
const cb = new ccui.CheckBox('bg.png', 'bg.png', 'cross.png', 'bg.png', 'cross.png');
cb.setSelected(true);
cb.addEventListener((sender, type) => {
    cb.setSelected(true);
    cc.log('Selected: ' + cb.isSelected());
}, this);
this.addChild(cb);
```

output:
The bug is that the event listener calls `cb.setSelected(true)` every time, overriding the toggle behavior. Remove that line and just read the state:

```typescript
const cb = new ccui.CheckBox('bg.png', 'bg.png', 'cross.png', 'bg.png', 'cross.png');
cb.setSelected(true);
cb.addEventListener((sender, type) => {
    cc.log('Selected: ' + cb.isSelected());
}, this);
this.addChild(cb);
```

The CheckBox automatically toggles its selected state on tap. Don't manually set it inside the event handler.

instruction:
Fix the bug. The button appears but has no visible title text:

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
btn.setTitleText('Play');
btn.setTitleFontSize(24);
btn.setTitleColor(cc.color(0, 0, 0, 0));
btn.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(btn);
```

output:
The bug is in `setTitleColor(cc.color(0, 0, 0, 0))` - the alpha channel is 0, making the text fully transparent. `setTitleColor` sets the RGB of the title label, but the alpha of 0 makes it invisible.

**Fix:** Use a visible color:

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
btn.setTitleText('Play');
btn.setTitleFontSize(24);
btn.setTitleColor(cc.color(0, 0, 0)); // black text, fully opaque
btn.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(btn);
```

