const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
btn.setPositionPercent(cc.p(0.5, 0.5));
parent.addChild(btn);
```

output:
The bug is that `setPositionType` was not changed to percentage mode. By default widgets use absolute positioning.

**Fix:** Set the position type to percent first:

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
btn.setPositionType(ccui.Widget.POSITION_PERCENT);
btn.setPositionPercent(cc.p(0.5, 0.5));
parent.addChild(btn);
```

instruction:
Fix the bug. Layout background color is set but nothing visible appears:

```typescript
const panel = new ccui.Layout();
panel.setSize(cc.size(300, 200));
panel.setBackGroundColor(cc.color(255, 0, 0));
panel.setPosition(50, 50);
this.addChild(panel);
```

output:
The bug is that `setBackGroundColorType` was never called. By default, the background color type is `BG_COLOR_NONE`, so the color is not rendered.

**Fix:** Set the background color type before setting the color:

```typescript
const panel = new ccui.Layout();
panel.setSize(cc.size(300, 200));
panel.setBackGroundColorType(ccui.Layout.BG_COLOR_SOLID);
panel.setBackGroundColor(cc.color(255, 0, 0));
panel.setBackGroundColorOpacity(255);
panel.setPosition(50, 50);
this.addChild(panel);
```

instruction:
Fix the bug. The PageView only shows one page and swipe doesn't work:

```typescript
const pv = new ccui.PageView();
pv.setSize(cc.size(400, 300));
for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
    const page = new ccui.Layout();
    pv.addPage(page);
}
this.addChild(pv);
```

output:
The bug is that the page layouts have no size set. Each page must have the same size as the PageView for proper rendering and swiping.

**Fix:** Set size on each page:

```typescript
const pv = new ccui.PageView();
pv.setSize(cc.size(400, 300));
for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
    const page = new ccui.Layout();
    page.setSize(cc.size(400, 300));
    page.setBackGroundColorType(ccui.Layout.BG_COLOR_SOLID);
    page.setBackGroundColor(cc.color(50 + i * 50, 100, 150));
    pv.addPage(page);
}
this.addChild(pv);
```

instruction:
Fix the bug. Calling `ignoreContentAdaptWithSize(false)` doesn't let the button resize:

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
btn.setSize(cc.size(200, 60));
btn.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(btn);
```

output:
The bug is that `ignoreContentAdaptWithSize` is not called. By default, widgets auto-fit to their texture size, ignoring `setSize()`.

**Fix:** Call `ignoreContentAdaptWithSize(false)` to allow manual sizing:

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
btn.ignoreContentAdaptWithSize(false);
btn.setSize(cc.size(200, 60));
btn.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(btn);
```

Alternatively, enable Scale9 which implicitly allows custom sizing:
```typescript
btn.setScale9Enabled(true);
btn.setSize(cc.size(200, 60));
```

instruction:
Fix the bug. The ScrollView crashes because inner container is too small:

```typescript
const sv = new ccui.ScrollView();
sv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
sv.setInnerContainerSize(cc.size(300, 200));
sv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);
this.addChild(sv);
```

output:
The bug is that the inner container height (200) is less than the ScrollView height (400). The inner container must be >= the ScrollView size in the scroll direction.

**Fix:** Make inner container at least as tall as the ScrollView:

```typescript
const sv = new ccui.ScrollView();
sv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
sv.setInnerContainerSize(cc.size(300, 400)); // minimum: same as scrollview
sv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);
this.addChild(sv);
```

Only set the inner container larger when you have content that exceeds the visible area.

