instruction:
Fix the bug. The Layout LINEAR_VERTICAL children all stack at position (0,0):

```typescript
const layout = new ccui.Layout();
layout.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
layout.setLayoutType(ccui.Layout.LINEAR_VERTICAL);
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    const text = new ccui.Text('Line ' + i, 'Arial', 18);
    text.setPosition(150, 350 - i * 40);
    layout.addChild(text);
}
this.addChild(layout);
```

output:
The bug is manually setting positions on children in a linear layout. In LINEAR_VERTICAL mode, the layout engine manages positions automatically. Manually setting positions conflicts with the layout.

**Fix:** Remove `setPosition` and use LayoutParameters instead:

```typescript
const layout = new ccui.Layout();
layout.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
layout.setLayoutType(ccui.Layout.LINEAR_VERTICAL);
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    const text = new ccui.Text('Line ' + i, 'Arial', 18);
    const param = new ccui.LinearLayoutParameter();
    param.setGravity(ccui.LinearLayoutParameter.CENTER_HORIZONTAL);
    param.setMargin(new ccui.Margin(0, 10, 0, 0));
    text.setLayoutParameter(param);
    layout.addChild(text);
}
layout.forceDoLayout();
this.addChild(layout);
```

instruction:
Fix the bug. The ImageView texture from a plist sprite frame doesn't load:

```typescript
const img = new ccui.ImageView('icon_gem.png');
img.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(img);
```

output:
The bug is that the texture type defaults to `LOCAL_TEXTURE`, meaning it looks for a standalone file. If `icon_gem.png` is a sprite frame from a plist atlas, you must specify `PLIST_TEXTURE`.

**Fix:** Pass the texture type:

```typescript
const img = new ccui.ImageView('icon_gem.png', ccui.Widget.PLIST_TEXTURE);
img.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(img);
```

Make sure the sprite sheet containing `icon_gem.png` has been loaded into `cc.spriteFrameCache` beforehand.

instruction:
Fix the bug. The ScrollView events never fire:

```typescript
const sv = new ccui.ScrollView();
sv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
sv.setInnerContainerSize(cc.size(300, 1000));
sv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);
sv.addTouchEventListener((sender, type) => {
    if (type === ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_SCROLL_TO_BOTTOM) {
        cc.log('reached bottom');
    }
}, this);
this.addChild(sv);
```

output:
The bug is using `addTouchEventListener` instead of `addEventListener`. ScrollView scroll events use `addEventListener`, while `addTouchEventListener` is for widget touch events (began/moved/ended/canceled).

**Fix:** Use `addEventListener`:

```typescript
const sv = new ccui.ScrollView();
sv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
sv.setInnerContainerSize(cc.size(300, 1000));
sv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);
sv.addEventListener((sender, type) => {
    if (type === ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_SCROLL_TO_BOTTOM) {
        cc.log('reached bottom');
    }
}, this);
this.addChild(sv);
```

instruction:
Fix the bug. The ListView item at index 5 cannot be retrieved after adding items:

```typescript
const lv = new ccui.ListView();
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    const item = new ccui.Text('Item ' + i, 'Arial', 18);
    lv.addChild(item);
}
const fifth = lv.getItem(5);
cc.log(fifth.getString()); // error: getString is not a function
```

output:
The bug is that `getItem` returns `ccui.Widget`, and you're calling `getString()` which is a method on `ccui.Text`. You need to cast the result:

```typescript
const lv = new ccui.ListView();
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    const item = new ccui.Text('Item ' + i, 'Arial', 18);
    lv.pushBackCustomItem(item);
}
const fifth = lv.getItem(5) as ccui.Text;
cc.log(fifth.getString());
```

Also note: use `pushBackCustomItem` instead of `addChild` for proper ListView item management.

instruction:
Fix the bug. The widget's `widgetParent` is null even though it's added to a Layout:

```typescript
const layout = new ccui.Layout();
const sprite = new cc.Sprite('bg.png');
layout.addChild(sprite);
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
layout.addChild(btn);
cc.log(sprite.widgetParent); // null??
cc.log(btn.widgetParent);    // works
```

output:
The `widgetParent` property only exists on `ccui.Widget` subclasses. `cc.Sprite` is not a widget, so it doesn't have this property.

This is expected behavior, not a bug in the engine. `widgetParent` returns the parent only if the parent is also a `ccui.Widget`. A `cc.Sprite` doesn't have widget properties at all.

**Fix:** If you need the parent of a non-widget child, use standard `cc.Node` methods:

```typescript
const layout = new ccui.Layout();
const sprite = new cc.Sprite('bg.png');
layout.addChild(sprite);
cc.log(sprite.getParent()); // returns the layout as cc.Node

const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
layout.addChild(btn);
cc.log(btn.widgetParent); // returns the layout as ccui.Widget
```

instruction:
Review this code for issues:

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png', 'btn_pressed.png');
btn.setTitleText('OK');
btn.setTitleFontSize(20);
btn.setSize(cc.size(150, 50));
btn.setPosition(200, 200);
btn.addClickEventListener(() => this.onConfirm());
this.addChild(btn);
```

output:
**Issue:** `setSize()` won't work as expected because the button auto-sizes to its texture by default.

**Fix:** Either call `ignoreContentAdaptWithSize(false)` or enable Scale9:

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png', 'btn_pressed.png');
btn.setTitleText('OK');
btn.setTitleFontSize(20);
btn.setScale9Enabled(true); // allows custom sizing
btn.setSize(cc.size(150, 50));
btn.setPosition(200, 200);
btn.addClickEventListener(() => this.onConfirm());
this.addChild(btn);
```

Without Scale9 or `ignoreContentAdaptWithSize(false)`, the button ignores `setSize()` and uses the texture's original dimensions.

instruction:
Review this ScrollView setup code:

```typescript
const sv = new ccui.ScrollView();
sv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
sv.setInnerContainerSize(cc.size(300, 400));
sv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_BOTH);
sv.setBounceEnabled(true);
this.addChild(sv);
```

output:
**Issues:**

1. **Inner container same size as ScrollView** - The inner container is 300x400, same as the ScrollView. Nothing will scroll because there's no overflow content.
2. **DIR_BOTH with equal sizes** - Using `DIR_BOTH` is unnecessary when sizes match in both axes.

**Fix:**

```typescript
const sv = new ccui.ScrollView();
sv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
sv.setInnerContainerSize(cc.size(600, 1200)); // larger than sv
sv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_BOTH);
sv.setBounceEnabled(true);
this.addChild(sv);
```

Only use `DIR_BOTH` when content exceeds the view in both width and height.

instruction:
Review this code for performance issues:

```typescript
for (let i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
    const btn = new ccui.Button('item.png', 'item_pressed.png');
    btn.setTitleText('Item ' + i);
    btn.setTitleFontSize(14);
    btn.setPosition(150, 990 - i * 50);
    sv.getInnerContainer().addChild(btn);
}
```

output:
**Issues:**

1. **1000 Button widgets** - Creating 1000 full Button widgets with textures is very heavy. Each Button has normal/pressed/disabled texture nodes. This will cause high memory usage and poor frame rate.
2. **No virtualization** - All 1000 items are created upfront and added to the scene graph.
3. **Calling getInnerContainer() 1000 times** - Minor but cache the reference.

**Fix:** Use ListView with item recycling or limit visible items:

```typescript
const container = sv.getInnerContainer();
const VISIBLE_COUNT = 20;

// Only create visible items, reuse on scroll
for (let i = 0; i < VISIBLE_COUNT; i++) {
    const item = new ccui.Text('Item ' + i, 'Arial', 14);
    item.setPosition(150, sv.getSize().height - i * 50);
    container.addChild(item);
}
```

For large lists, implement virtual scrolling: create only enough items to fill the viewport and recycle them as the user scrolls.

instruction:
Review this code:

```typescript
const layout = new ccui.Layout();
layout.setLayoutType(ccui.Layout.LINEAR_VERTICAL);
layout.setSize(cc.size(300, 500));

const btn1 = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
btn1.setPosition(150, 450);
layout.addChild(btn1);

const btn2 = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
btn2.setPosition(150, 350);
layout.addChild(btn2);
```

output:
**Issue:** Setting explicit positions on children in a `LINEAR_VERTICAL` layout is pointless. The linear layout engine overrides manual positions and arranges children automatically top-to-bottom.

**Fix:** Remove setPosition calls and use LayoutParameters for spacing/alignment:

```typescript
const layout = new ccui.Layout();
layout.setLayoutType(ccui.Layout.LINEAR_VERTICAL);
layout.setSize(cc.size(300, 500));

const btn1 = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
const param1 = new ccui.LinearLayoutParameter();
param1.setGravity(ccui.LinearLayoutParameter.CENTER_HORIZONTAL);
param1.setMargin(new ccui.Margin(0, 10, 0, 0));
btn1.setLayoutParameter(param1);
layout.addChild(btn1);

const btn2 = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
const param2 = new ccui.LinearLayoutParameter();
param2.setGravity(ccui.LinearLayoutParameter.CENTER_HORIZONTAL);
param2.setMargin(new ccui.Margin(0, 10, 0, 0));
btn2.setLayoutParameter(param2);
layout.addChild(btn2);

layout.forceDoLayout();
```

instruction:
Review this code for correctness:

```typescript
const tf = new ccui.TextField('Enter name', 'Arial', 18);
tf.setMaxLength(10);
tf.setPasswordEnabled(true);
tf.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(tf);
```

output:
**Issue:** `setMaxLength(10)` won't take effect because `setMaxLengthEnabled(true)` was not called first. The max length feature is disabled by default.

**Fix:**

```typescript
const tf = new ccui.TextField('Enter name', 'Arial', 18);
tf.setMaxLengthEnabled(true);
tf.setMaxLength(10);
tf.setPasswordEnabled(true);
tf.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(tf);
```

Also, having a password field with a placeholder "Enter name" is misleading. Consider using separate fields for username and password.

instruction:
Review this event handling code:

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
btn.addTouchEventListener((sender, type) => {
    this.handleTouch();
}, this);
btn.addClickEventListener(() => {
    this.handleClick();
});
btn.addTouchEventListener((sender, type) => {
    this.handleTouch2();
}, this);
```

output:
**Issues:**

1. **Overwritten listener** - The second `addTouchEventListener` call overwrites the first one. Only `handleTouch2` will fire, not `handleTouch`. Each widget supports only one touch event listener.
2. **Redundant handlers** - Having both `addTouchEventListener` and `addClickEventListener` is fine but can be confusing. The click listener fires on TOUCH_ENDED specifically.

**Fix:** Combine logic into one touch listener or use only click:

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
btn.addTouchEventListener((sender, type) => {
    this.handleTouch();
    this.handleTouch2();
    if (type === ccui.Widget.TOUCH_ENDED) {
        this.handleClick();
    }
}, this);
```

instruction:
Review this ListView code:

```typescript
const lv = new ccui.ListView();
lv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
lv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);

for (let i = 0; i < 20; i++) {
    const item = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
    item.setTitleText('Item ' + i);
    lv.addChild(item);
}

lv.removeItem(5);
lv.removeItem(10);
```

output:
**Issues:**

1. **Using `addChild` instead of `pushBackCustomItem`** - While `addChild` works, `pushBackCustomItem` is the proper ListView API for adding items and ensures correct list management.
2. **Index shift on removal** - After `removeItem(5)`, the list has 19 items and indices shift. So `removeItem(10)` removes what was originally item 11, not 10.

**Fix:**

```typescript
const lv = new ccui.ListView();
lv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
lv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);

for (let i = 0; i < 20; i++) {
    const item = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
    item.setTitleText('Item ' + i);
    lv.pushBackCustomItem(item);
}

// Remove higher index first to avoid index shift
lv.removeItem(10);
lv.removeItem(5);
```

instruction:
Review this code:

```typescript
const panel = new ccui.Layout();
panel.setSize(cc.size(300, 200));
panel.setClippingEnabled(true);
panel.setBackGroundColorType(ccui.Layout.BG_COLOR_SOLID);
panel.setBackGroundColor(cc.color(0, 0, 0, 180));
this.addChild(panel);
```

output:
**Issue:** `setBackGroundColor` takes `cc.Color` for RGB values, but the alpha (180) passed inside `cc.color()` may be ignored by the background color system. Layout background opacity must be set separately with `setBackGroundColorOpacity`.

**Fix:**

```typescript
const panel = new ccui.Layout();
panel.setSize(cc.size(300, 200));
panel.setClippingEnabled(true);
panel.setBackGroundColorType(ccui.Layout.BG_COLOR_SOLID);
panel.setBackGroundColor(cc.color(0, 0, 0));
panel.setBackGroundColorOpacity(180);
this.addChild(panel);
```

Always use `setBackGroundColorOpacity()` to control the alpha of layout backgrounds.

instruction:
Review this code:

```typescript
class SettingsScene extends cc.Scene {
    onEnter() {
        super.onEnter();
        const slider = new ccui.Slider();
        slider.loadBarTexture('bar.png');
        slider.loadSlidBallTextures('ball.png', 'ball.png', 'ball.png');
        slider.setMaxPercent(200);
        slider.setPercent(150);
        this.addChild(slider);
    }
}
```

output:
**Issues:**

1. **No position set** - The slider will default to (0,0), likely off-screen or in the corner.
2. **No progress bar texture** - Without `loadProgressBarTexture`, there's no visual feedback for the filled portion.
3. **setMaxPercent(200)** with **setPercent(150)** - While technically valid, using a non-standard max percent can confuse code that expects 0-100 range.

**Fix:**

```typescript
class SettingsScene extends cc.Scene {
    onEnter() {
        super.onEnter();
        const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();
        const slider = new ccui.Slider();
        slider.loadBarTexture('bar.png');
        slider.loadSlidBallTextures('ball.png', 'ball.png', 'ball.png');
        slider.loadProgressBarTexture('progress.png');
        slider.setPercent(75);
        slider.setPosition(winSize.width / 2, winSize.height / 2);
        this.addChild(slider);
    }
}
```

instruction:
Review this code:

```typescript
const sv = new ccui.ScrollView();
sv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
sv.setInnerContainerSize(cc.size(300, 1200));
sv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);
sv.setInertiaScrollEnabled(false);
sv.setBounceEnabled(true);
sv.scrollToBottom(0, true);
this.addChild(sv);
```

output:
**Issues:**

1. **scrollToBottom with duration 0** - Passing `0` for the time parameter makes this effectively a jump, but `jumpToBottom()` is more appropriate and clearer.
2. **Bounce without inertia** - `setBounceEnabled(true)` with `setInertiaScrollEnabled(false)` is an unusual combination. Bounce typically works with inertia; without it, the bounce effect is less noticeable since the scroll stops immediately when the finger lifts.
3. **scrollToBottom before addChild** - Scrolling before the widget is on stage may not work reliably.

**Fix:**

```typescript
const sv = new ccui.ScrollView();
sv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
sv.setInnerContainerSize(cc.size(300, 1200));
sv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);
sv.setInertiaScrollEnabled(true);
sv.setBounceEnabled(true);
this.addChild(sv);
sv.jumpToBottom(); // after adding to scene
```

`LOCAL_TEXTURE` and `PLIST_TEXTURE` are texture type constants that tell UI widgets how to load images:

**`ccui.Widget.LOCAL_TEXTURE`** — Loads from a standalone image file on disk:
```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('res/images/btn.png', '', '', ccui.Widget.LOCAL_TEXTURE);
```

**`ccui.Widget.PLIST_TEXTURE`** — Loads from a sprite frame in `cc.spriteFrameCache` (typically from a .plist atlas):
```typescript
// First load the atlas
cc.spriteFrameCache.addSpriteFrames('res/ui.plist');
// Then reference frame names
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png', '', '', ccui.Widget.PLIST_TEXTURE);
```

Use `PLIST_TEXTURE` when your images are packed into a texture atlas for better performance (fewer draw calls, better memory usage). Use `LOCAL_TEXTURE` for standalone images not in any atlas.

`addTouchEventListener` provides detailed touch phase information, while `addClickEventListener` is a simplified tap handler.

**`addTouchEventListener`** receives four event types:
```typescript
widget.addTouchEventListener((sender, type) => {
    switch (type) {
        case ccui.Widget.TOUCH_BEGAN:    // finger down
        case ccui.Widget.TOUCH_MOVED:    // finger dragging
        case ccui.Widget.TOUCH_ENDED:    // finger lifted (successful tap)
        case ccui.Widget.TOUCH_CANCELED: // touch interrupted
    }
}, this);
```

**`addClickEventListener`** only fires on a successful tap (equivalent to TOUCH_ENDED):
```typescript
widget.addClickEventListener(() => {
    // Only called when tap completes
});
```

Use `addClickEventListener` for simple button taps. Use `addTouchEventListener` when you need to track drag, press-and-hold, or cancel states.

These four layout types control how child widgets are positioned inside a `ccui.Layout`:

**`ABSOLUTE` (default)** — Free positioning. You set each child's position manually with `setPosition()`. No automatic arrangement.

**`LINEAR_HORIZONTAL`** — Children flow left to right. Order is determined by `addChild` order. Use `ccui.LinearLayoutParameter` for gravity and margins:
```typescript
layout.setLayoutType(ccui.Layout.LINEAR_HORIZONTAL);
```

**`LINEAR_VERTICAL`** — Children flow top to bottom. Same parameter system as horizontal:
```typescript
layout.setLayoutType(ccui.Layout.LINEAR_VERTICAL);
const param = new ccui.LinearLayoutParameter();
param.setGravity(ccui.LinearLayoutParameter.CENTER_HORIZONTAL);
param.setMargin(new ccui.Margin(0, 10, 0, 0));
child.setLayoutParameter(param);
```

**`RELATIVE`** — Children are positioned relative to the parent or sibling widgets. Uses `ccui.RelativeLayoutParameter`:
```typescript
layout.setLayoutType(ccui.Layout.RELATIVE);
const rel = new ccui.RelativeLayoutParameter();
rel.setAlign(ccui.RelativeLayoutParameter.PARENT_TOP_LEFT);
rel.setRelativeName('myWidget');
child.setLayoutParameter(rel);
```

For linear and relative layouts, call `layout.forceDoLayout()` after adding children to trigger positioning.

`ccui.Margin` defines spacing around a widget when used inside a linear or relative layout.

```typescript
const margin = new ccui.Margin(left, top, right, bottom);
```

It is used with `ccui.LinearLayoutParameter` and `ccui.RelativeLayoutParameter`:

```typescript
const param = new ccui.LinearLayoutParameter();
param.setMargin(new ccui.Margin(10, 5, 10, 5));
// left: 10px, top: 5px, right: 10px, bottom: 5px
widget.setLayoutParameter(param);
```

**Important notes:**
- Margins only take effect when the parent Layout uses `LINEAR_HORIZONTAL`, `LINEAR_VERTICAL`, or `RELATIVE` layout types.
- In `ABSOLUTE` layout, margins are ignored since children are freely positioned.
- The margin order is `(left, top, right, bottom)`, similar to CSS but passed as constructor arguments.
- After changing margins, call `layout.forceDoLayout()` to recalculate positions.

`updateSizeAndPosition` recalculates a widget's size and position based on its parent's size. This is useful when the parent resizes and widgets use percentage-based sizing/positioning.

```typescript
widget.updateSizeAndPosition(parentSize: cc.Size): void
```

**When it's called:**
- Automatically by the layout system when parent size changes
- Manually when you need to force a recalculation

**Example:**
```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
btn.setSizeType(ccui.Widget.SIZE_PERCENT);
btn.setSizePercent(cc.p(0.5, 0.1));
btn.setPositionType(ccui.Widget.POSITION_PERCENT);
btn.setPositionPercent(cc.p(0.5, 0.5));
parentLayout.addChild(btn);

// If parent resizes:
parentLayout.setSize(cc.size(600, 400));
btn.updateSizeAndPosition(cc.size(600, 400));
```

Usually you don't call this directly. The layout system handles it. Use `layout.forceDoLayout()` or `layout.requestDoLayout()` to trigger layout recalculation for all children.

ScrollView fires these event types through its `addEventListener` callback:

```typescript
sv.addEventListener((sender, type) => {
    switch (type) {
        // Scroll reached edges:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_SCROLL_TO_TOP:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_SCROLL_TO_BOTTOM:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_SCROLL_TO_LEFT:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_SCROLL_TO_RIGHT:

        // Actively scrolling:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_SCROLLING:

        // Bounce events (when bounce is enabled):
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_BOUNCE_TOP:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_BOUNCE_BOTTOM:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_BOUNCE_LEFT:
        case ccui.ScrollView.EVENT_BOUNCE_RIGHT:
    }
}, this);
```

Common use cases:
- `EVENT_SCROLL_TO_BOTTOM` — infinite scroll / load more
- `EVENT_SCROLLING` — update UI during scroll (parallax, headers)
- `EVENT_BOUNCE_*` — visual feedback on overscroll

Note: These events use `addEventListener`, not `addTouchEventListener`.

`setItemModel` defines a template widget that `pushBackDefaultItem` clones to create new list items.

**Workflow:**
1. Create a template widget and configure it
2. Set it as the model with `setItemModel`
3. Call `pushBackDefaultItem()` to clone and add it

```typescript
// 1. Create template
const model = new ccui.Button('item_bg.png');
model.setScale9Enabled(true);
model.setSize(cc.size(280, 45));
model.setTitleText('Default');
model.setTitleFontSize(16);

// 2. Set as model
lv.setItemModel(model);

// 3. Clone and add
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    lv.pushBackDefaultItem();
    // Customize each clone:
    const item = lv.getItem(i) as ccui.Button;
    item.setTitleText('Item ' + i);
}
```

**vs pushBackCustomItem:**
- `pushBackDefaultItem()` — clones the model
- `pushBackCustomItem(widget)` — adds a specific widget you created

Use the model approach when all items share the same structure. Use custom items when each item is different.

Both trigger layout recalculation, but with different timing:

**`forceDoLayout()`** — Recalculates layout immediately, synchronously:
```typescript
layout.addChild(widget);
layout.forceDoLayout(); // positions updated right now
const pos = widget.getPosition(); // correct position
```

**`requestDoLayout()`** — Marks the layout as dirty, recalculation happens on the next frame:
```typescript
layout.addChild(widget);
layout.requestDoLayout(); // will update next frame
// widget position may not be updated yet this frame
```

**When to use which:**
- Use `forceDoLayout()` when you need correct positions immediately (e.g., to read a child's position right after adding it).
- Use `requestDoLayout()` when making multiple changes and want to batch the recalculation for better performance.

```typescript
// Multiple changes - use request to batch
for (let i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
    layout.addChild(createItem(i));
}
layout.requestDoLayout(); // one recalculation instead of 100

// Single change needing immediate result - use force
layout.addChild(newItem);
layout.forceDoLayout();
const bounds = newItem.getBoundingBox();
```

Combine Button touch events with scale actions:

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('menu_btn.png', 'menu_btn_pressed.png');
btn.setTitleText('START');
btn.setTitleFontSize(24);
btn.setPosition(240, 160);

btn.addTouchEventListener((sender, type) => {
    sender.stopAllActions();
    if (type === ccui.Widget.TOUCH_BEGAN) {
        sender.runAction(cc.scaleTo(0.1, 1.15).easing(cc.easeBackOut()));
    } else if (type === ccui.Widget.TOUCH_ENDED) {
        sender.runAction(cc.sequence(
            cc.scaleTo(0.1, 1.0),
            cc.callFunc(() => this.startGame())
        ));
    } else if (type === ccui.Widget.TOUCH_CANCELED) {
        sender.runAction(cc.scaleTo(0.15, 1.0));
    }
}, this);

// Idle breathing animation
btn.runAction(cc.repeatForever(cc.sequence(
    cc.scaleTo(1.0, 1.05).easing(cc.easeSineInOut()),
    cc.scaleTo(1.0, 1.0).easing(cc.easeSineInOut())
)));

this.addChild(btn);
```

