Use the `flippedX` property or `setFlippedX` (if available via the `flippedX` property):

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('arrow_right.png');
btn.flippedX = true; // mirrors horizontally to point left
btn.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(btn);
```

Similarly, `flippedY = true` mirrors vertically. This is useful for reusing directional arrow textures without creating separate assets for each direction.

Set the direction to `DIR_BOTH` and make the inner container larger in both dimensions:

```typescript
const sv = new ccui.ScrollView();
sv.setSize(cc.size(300, 300));
sv.setInnerContainerSize(cc.size(800, 800));
sv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_BOTH);
sv.setBounceEnabled(true);
sv.setInertiaScrollEnabled(true);
sv.setPosition(90, 10);

const content = new cc.Sprite('large_texture.png');
content.setAnchorPoint(cc.p(0, 0));
sv.getInnerContainer().addChild(content);

this.addChild(sv);
```

Both the inner width and height must exceed the ScrollView dimensions for bidirectional scrolling.

instruction:
Complete the TODO to remove a specific page from a PageView:

```typescript
const pv = new ccui.PageView();
// ... pages added ...
// TODO: remove the page at index 2
```

output:
You cannot remove by index directly. Get the page first, then remove it:

```typescript
const pv = new ccui.PageView();
// ... pages added ...
const pageToRemove = pv.getItem(2) as ccui.Layout;
pv.removePage(pageToRemove);
```

`removePage` takes a `ccui.Layout` reference, not an index. Use `getItem(index)` from the inherited ListView API or keep your own reference to the page.

instruction:
Fix the bug. The ccui.Text wraps incorrectly and text is cut off:

```typescript
const text = new ccui.Text('This is a very long text that should wrap properly.', 'Arial', 16);
text.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(text);
```

output:
The bug is that no text area size is set, so the text renders in a single line and may extend beyond the screen.

**Fix:** Set a text area size to enable word wrapping:

```typescript
const text = new ccui.Text('This is a very long text that should wrap properly.', 'Arial', 16);
text.setTextAreaSize(cc.size(250, 0)); // width=250, height=0 means auto height
text.setTextHorizontalAlignment(cc.TEXT_ALIGNMENT_LEFT);
text.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(text);
```

Setting the width constrains line length, and height=0 allows the text to grow vertically as needed.

`click()` and `addClickEventListener` serve different purposes:

**`addClickEventListener(callback)`** — Registers a function to be called when the user taps the widget:
```typescript
btn.addClickEventListener(() => {
    cc.log('User tapped the button');
});
```

**`click()`** — Programmatically triggers a tap, firing all registered listeners. Useful for testing/automation:
```typescript
btn.click(); // simulates a user tap, fires the click listener above
```

Think of `addClickEventListener` as "listen for clicks" and `click()` as "fake a click". You must register a listener first for `click()` to have any observable effect.

Use `setInnerContainerPosition` to directly control the scroll offset:

```typescript
const sv = new ccui.ScrollView();
sv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
sv.setInnerContainerSize(cc.size(300, 1200));
sv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);
this.addChild(sv);

// Scroll so that content at y=600 is visible at the top
sv.setInnerContainerPosition(cc.p(0, -(600 - 400)));
```

The inner container position is negative in the scroll direction. For vertical scrolling, y=0 means the top of the inner container is at the top of the view, and negative values scroll downward.

instruction:
Review this code for potential issues:

```typescript
const lv = new ccui.ListView();
lv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);
lv.setItemsMargin(10);
for (let i = 0; i < 50; i++) {
    const item = new ccui.Button('item.png');
    item.setTitleText('Item ' + i);
    lv.pushBackCustomItem(item);
}
this.addChild(lv);
```

output:
**Issues:**

1. **No size set on the ListView** - Without `setSize()`, the ListView has zero dimensions and nothing is visible.
2. **No bounce or scroll bar** - For 50 items, users would benefit from scroll feedback.

**Fix:**

```typescript
const lv = new ccui.ListView();
lv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
lv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);
lv.setItemsMargin(10);
lv.setBounceEnabled(true);
lv.setScrollBarEnabled(true);

for (let i = 0; i < 50; i++) {
    const item = new ccui.Button('item.png');
    item.setTitleText('Item ' + i);
    lv.pushBackCustomItem(item);
}

lv.setPosition(50, 50);
this.addChild(lv);
```

Position the panel off-screen left, then use a moveTo action:

```typescript
const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();
const panel = new ccui.Layout();
panel.setSize(cc.size(250, winSize.height));
panel.setBackGroundColorType(ccui.Layout.BG_COLOR_SOLID);
panel.setBackGroundColor(cc.color(30, 30, 50));
panel.setBackGroundColorOpacity(240);

// Start off-screen to the left
panel.setPosition(-250, 0);
this.addChild(panel, 100);

// Slide in
panel.runAction(cc.moveTo(0.3, cc.p(0, 0)).easing(cc.easeBackOut()));

// To close later:
function closePanel(): void {
    panel.runAction(cc.sequence(
        cc.moveTo(0.2, cc.p(-250, 0)).easing(cc.easeBackIn()),
        cc.callFunc(() => panel.removeFromParent())
    ));
}
```

`focused` and `requestFocus()` support keyboard and gamepad UI navigation:

**`isFocused()`** — Returns true if this widget currently has focus:
```typescript
const hasFocus: boolean = widget.isFocused();
```

**`setFocused(focus)`** — Directly sets the focus state:
```typescript
widget.setFocused(true);
```

**`requestFocus()`** — Requests focus through the focus system, which handles unfocusing the previously focused widget:
```typescript
widget.requestFocus(); // preferred over setFocused(true)
```

**Best practice:** Use `requestFocus()` rather than `setFocused(true)` because it properly manages the focus chain. `setFocused` is a lower-level call that doesn't notify the focus management system.

```typescript
// Navigate to next button
const buttons: ccui.Button[] = [btn1, btn2, btn3];
let focusIdx = 0;

function focusNext(): void {
    focusIdx = (focusIdx + 1) % buttons.length;
    buttons[focusIdx].requestFocus();
}
```

Call `getNormalTextureSize()` after loading the normal texture to get its original pixel dimensions:

```typescript
const btn = new ccui.Button('big_texture.png');
const texSize: cc.Size = btn.getNormalTextureSize();
cc.log('Texture size: ' + texSize.width + 'x' + texSize.height);

// Scale button to half the texture size
btn.ignoreContentAdaptWithSize(false);
btn.setSize(cc.size(texSize.width / 2, texSize.height / 2));
btn.setPosition(200, 200);
this.addChild(btn);
```

This is useful for responsive layouts where button size should adapt to the loaded asset dimensions rather than being hardcoded.

Add items with zero opacity and stagger fade-in actions:

```typescript
const lv = new ccui.ListView();
lv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
lv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);
lv.setItemsMargin(8);
lv.setPosition(90, 20);
this.addChild(lv);

const itemNames = ['Sword', 'Shield', 'Potion', 'Armor', 'Ring', 'Scroll'];

itemNames.forEach((name, i) => {
    const item = new ccui.Layout();
    item.setSize(cc.size(280, 45));
    item.setBackGroundColorType(ccui.Layout.BG_COLOR_SOLID);
    item.setBackGroundColor(cc.color(50, 50, 70));
    item.setBackGroundColorOpacity(200);

    const label = new ccui.Text(name, 'Arial', 18);
    label.setPosition(140, 22);
    item.addChild(label);

    item.setOpacity(0);
    lv.pushBackCustomItem(item);

    // Staggered animation
    item.runAction(cc.sequence(
        cc.delayTime(i * 0.12),
        cc.spawn(
            cc.fadeIn(0.25),
            cc.moveBy(0.25, cc.p(30, 0)).easing(cc.easeOut(2))
        )
    ));
});
```

instruction:
Fix the bug. The ScrollView inertia scroll feels too fast and uncontrollable:

```typescript
const sv = new ccui.ScrollView();
sv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
sv.setInnerContainerSize(cc.size(300, 2000));
sv.setDirection(ccui.ScrollView.DIR_VERTICAL);
sv.setInertiaScrollEnabled(true);
sv.setBounceEnabled(true);
this.addChild(sv);
```

output:
This isn't strictly a bug — the code is correct. However, if inertia feels too fast, there is no direct API to set inertia speed on ccui.ScrollView in Cocos2d-x v3.x JS. The options are:

**Option 1:** Disable inertia entirely if it's problematic:
```typescript
sv.setInertiaScrollEnabled(false);
```

**Option 2:** Reduce bounce and scroll bar feedback to make it feel more controlled:
```typescript
sv.setInertiaScrollEnabled(true);
sv.setBounceEnabled(false);
sv.setScrollBarEnabled(true);
sv.setScrollBarAutoHideEnabled(true);
sv.setScrollBarAutoHideTime(0.5);
```

**Option 3:** Subdivide content into a PageView for discrete paging instead of free scroll:
```typescript
// Replace ScrollView with PageView for controlled paging
const pv = new ccui.PageView();
pv.setSize(cc.size(300, 400));
```

The inertia deceleration rate is internal to the engine in this version.

The PageView type declaration:

```typescript
declare class PageView extends ccui.Layout {
    constructor();

    addPage(page: ccui.Layout): void;
    removePage(page: ccui.Layout): void;
    scrollToPage(idx: number): void;
    getCurrentPageIndex(): number;
    addEventListener(
        callback: (sender: ccui.PageView, eventType: number) => void,
        target?: object
    ): void;
    setCustomScrollThreshold(threshold: number): void;
    setUsingCustomScrollThreshold(flag: boolean): void;
}
```

Typed usage:
```typescript
const pv: ccui.PageView = new ccui.PageView();
pv.setSize(cc.size(480, 320));

const page: ccui.Layout = new ccui.Layout();
page.setSize(cc.size(480, 320));
pv.addPage(page);

const idx: number = pv.getCurrentPageIndex();
pv.scrollToPage(2);

pv.addEventListener((sender: ccui.PageView, type: number): void => {
    cc.log('Page changed to: ' + sender.getCurrentPageIndex());
}, this);
```

Create a full-screen touch-enabled overlay Layout:

```typescript
function showConfirmDialog(message: string, onConfirm: () => void, onCancel: () => void): ccui.Layout {
    const winSize = cc.director.getWinSize();

    // Full-screen overlay that swallows all touches
    const overlay = new ccui.Layout();
    overlay.setSize(winSize);
    overlay.setPosition(0, 0);
    overlay.setTouchEnabled(true); // blocks touches to widgets behind
    overlay.setBackGroundColorType(ccui.Layout.BG_COLOR_SOLID);
    overlay.setBackGroundColor(cc.color(0, 0, 0));
    overlay.setBackGroundColorOpacity(150);

    const dialog = new ccui.Layout();
    dialog.setSize(cc.size(300, 160));
    dialog.setBackGroundColorType(ccui.Layout.BG_COLOR_SOLID);
    dialog.setBackGroundColor(cc.color(50, 50, 70));
    dialog.setBackGroundColorOpacity(255);
    dialog.setPosition((winSize.width - 300) / 2, (winSize.height - 160) / 2);
    overlay.addChild(dialog);

    const msgLabel = new ccui.Text(message, 'Arial', 18);
    msgLabel.setTextAreaSize(cc.size(260, 60));
    msgLabel.setPosition(150, 110);
    dialog.addChild(msgLabel);

    const okBtn = new ccui.Button('btn_ok.png');
    okBtn.setTitleText('OK');
    okBtn.setPosition(90, 30);
    okBtn.addClickEventListener(() => { overlay.removeFromParent(); onConfirm(); });
    dialog.addChild(okBtn);

    const cancelBtn = new ccui.Button('btn_cancel.png');
    cancelBtn.setTitleText('Cancel');
    cancelBtn.setPosition(210, 30);
    cancelBtn.addClickEventListener(() => { overlay.removeFromParent(); onCancel(); });
    dialog.addChild(cancelBtn);

    return overlay;
}

// Usage:
const dlg = showConfirmDialog('Quit the game?', () => cc.director.end(), () => {});
this.addChild(dlg, 9999);
```

The key is `overlay.setTouchEnabled(true)` on a full-screen Layout, which intercepts all touches and prevents them from reaching widgets behind the dialog.

Use `getItems()` and `getItemsCount()` to iterate over all items:

```typescript
interface ExportedItem {
    index: number;
    name: string;
}

function exportListData(lv: ccui.ListView): ExportedItem[] {
    const result: ExportedItem[] = [];
    const count: number = lv.getItemsCount();

    for (let i = 0; i < count; i++) {
        const widget: ccui.Widget = lv.getItem(i);
        // Assuming items are Buttons with title text
        const btn = widget as ccui.Button;
        result.push({
            index: i,
            name: btn.getTitleText()
        });
    }

    return result;
}

// Or using getItems():
const allWidgets: ccui.Widget[] = lv.getItems();
allWidgets.forEach((w: ccui.Widget, idx: number) => {
    cc.log('Item ' + idx + ': ' + lv.getIndex(w));
});
```

Set a background image with Scale9 enabled to stretch/tile it:

```typescript
const panel = new ccui.Layout();
panel.setSize(cc.size(400, 300));
panel.setBackGroundImage('panel_bg_9slice.png');
panel.setBackGroundImageScale9Enabled(true);
panel.setBackGroundImageCapInsets(cc.rect(20, 20, 60, 60));
panel.setPosition(40, 10);
this.addChild(panel);
```

The cap insets `cc.rect(20, 20, 60, 60)` means:
- The 20px borders on each side are preserved
- The center 60x60 region stretches to fill the remaining space
- Corners remain at their original size

This is the standard technique for scalable dialog boxes and panel backgrounds in Cocos2d-x UI.

The `actionTag` property identifies widgets when loaded from Cocos Studio or similar UI editors:

```typescript
// When building UI programmatically:
const btn = new ccui.Button('btn.png');
btn.actionTag = 1001;
panel.addChild(btn);

// When loading from editor, widgets have actionTags set by the tool.
// You can find widgets by action tag:
function findWidgetByActionTag(root: ccui.Widget, tag: number): ccui.Widget | null {
    if (root.actionTag === tag) return root;
    const children = root.getChildren();
    for (let i = 0; i < children.length; i++) {
        const child = children[i] as ccui.Widget;
        if (child.actionTag !== undefined) {
            const found = findWidgetByActionTag(child, tag);
            if (found) return found;
        }
    }
    return null;
}

const myBtn = findWidgetByActionTag(rootWidget, 1001) as ccui.Button;
if (myBtn) {
    myBtn.addClickEventListener(() => this.onStart());
}
```

Note: For name-based lookup, prefer `ccui.helper.seekWidgetByName` which is built-in and recursive.
